The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
		 Sunday, June 27, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Krishnagar (Nadia), June 26: Police today arrested the father of a Madhyamik examinee for assaulting the headmaster of his sons school. 				 																																	Bhajan Biswas, a bank employee, assaulted Sailen Singha, the headmaster of Krishanagar High School, at his office accusing him of awarding low marks to his son in the Madhyamik oral tests . 				 																																	Calcutta: Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee admitted that farmers had suffered losses in sunflower cultivation promoted by the government due to its faulty policy. His government had earlier insinuated that the crop failed as the seeds were planted late. He called for efforts to get over our weakness in production of seeds, bio-fertilisers and bio-pesticides. 				 																																	Howrah: Residents of Andul blocked the Andul road for over two hours after a speeding vehicle ran over a youth. Police said he was declared dead when he was taken to the Howrah district hospital. 				 																																	Howrah: Police observed International Anti-Drug Day by organising rallies, in which more than 400 students participated. A drama, Khola Janala, was staged at a drug rehabilitation centre in Dasnagar.
